  "prompt": "Is Ravana's golden lanka still in Sri Lanka?",
  "response": "The concept of Ravana's golden Lanka is deeply rooted in Hindu mythology, specifically in the epic Ramayana. According to the legend, Lanka was a prosperous and magnificent city ruled by Ravana, the demon king. However, there is no historical or archaeological evidence to confirm the existence of a \"golden Lanka\" as described in the myths.\n\nModern-day Sri Lanka, where the mythical Lanka is believed to have been located, does not have any remnants that can be directly associated with Ravana's golden city. The ancient city of Anuradhapura, one of the oldest continuously inhabited cities in the world, and other historical sites like Sigiriya and Polonnaruwa, showcase the rich history of Sri Lanka, but they are not linked to the mythical golden Lanka.\n\nIn summary, while the legend of Ravana's golden Lanka is part of cultural and religious lore, there is no evidence to suggest that such a city exists or ever existed in the physical form described in the Ramayana.",
